^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|BTW, I do not teach that you should bid a grand slam when you have all the key cards and the trump Queen. In fact, I teach that you should only bid a grand slam if you are just about positive it will make (80% or more). If you never bid any grand slams, in the long run you will come out ahead. You usually get a good result just for bidding a small slam.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you bid a grand slam that goes down, not only do you lose the probable good result of the small slam (probably averages at least 7 imps), but you give the opponents a large score (in the range of 12 imps). You will probably gain 7 imps of so for bidding the grand slam. So, you are risking losing 20 imps for a possible gain of 7 imps. That means the odds of making the grand better greatly be in your favor.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What you may be thinking of regarding my teaching is, once you decide you have enough points for a small slam and launch into RKCB, the decision of whether or not to bid small slam is cut and dried. You bid the small slam if you have all the key cards or if you have 4 key cards and the trump Queen.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this board, grand slam is not even a 50% proposition. You need a 3-2 heart break and a 3-3 diamond break. I put the odds at less than 40%.|
