^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There were 3 important points on this hand. a) When partner reverses and you have at least 10 points, you are captain of the hand and must make forcing bids until you reach game
b) On many hands, when missing 4 hearts to the Queen, bidding clues make the finesse a higher percentage than the drop. The most common occurrence is when an opponent has shown a 5+ card suit. In that case, the odds very much favor the other opponent having the trump Queen.|
PG| ***** 85 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The reasoning is as follows: If you know 5 of one opponents cards, you only don't know 8 of their other cards. But there are more unknown cards in the other opponents hand. Therefore, it is more likely that one of the unknown cards is the trump Queen. Even if you don't understand the math, the principle is important. If one opponent shows a 5+ card suit, play the other opponent for the trump Queen with a 9 card fit missing the Queen.|
PG| ***** 86 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|c) Often if you run your winning tricks, you make it difficult for the opponents to discard correctly, and you end up with an extra trick you are not entitled to. That is the basis for  a squeeze, but even when you do not have a real squeeze, it is very easy for the defenders to make a discarding mistake.|
